1
00:03:58,989 --> 00:04:00,698
So you were raised in a zoo?

2
00:04:00,866 --> 00:04:02,074
Born and raised.

3
00:04:02,242 --> 00:04:05,703
In Pondicherry, in what was
the French part of India.

4
00:04:05,871 --> 00:04:07,747
My father owned the zoo...

5
00:04:07,915 --> 00:04:11,208
and I was delivered on short notice
by a herpetologist...

6
00:04:11,376 --> 00:04:14,879
who was there to check
on the Bengal monitor lizard.

7
00:04:15,464 --> 00:04:17,423
Mother and I were both healthy...

8
00:04:17,591 --> 00:04:19,216
but the poor lizard escaped...

9
00:04:19,384 --> 00:04:22,428
and was trampled by a frightened cassowary.

10
00:04:24,681 --> 00:04:26,891
The way of karma, huh?

11
00:04:27,392 --> 00:04:29,435
The way of God.

12
00:04:30,228 --> 00:04:32,146
That's quite a story.

13
00:04:32,606 --> 00:04:34,023
I had assumed your father was a

14
00:04:34,149 --> 00:04:35,524
mathematician because of your name.

15
00:04:35,692 --> 00:04:38,778
Far from it,
I was named after a swimming pool.

16
00:04:39,613 --> 00:04:41,781
There is a swimming pool named "Pi"?

17
00:04:43,075 --> 00:04:45,201
You see, my uncle Francis was born

18
00:04:45,327 --> 00:04:47,453
with too much water in his lungs.

19
00:04:47,788 --> 00:04:49,872
They say the doctors swung Francis around

20
00:04:49,998 --> 00:04:52,083
by the ankles to clear the water out. . .

21
00:04:52,250 --> 00:04:54,919
and that's what gave him
the huge chest and skinny legs. . .

22
00:04:55,087 --> 00:04:57,380
that made him such a great swimmer.

23
00:04:58,298 --> 00:05:00,007
Is Francis actually your uncle?

24
00:05:00,133 --> 00:05:01,884
He said he was friends with your father.

25
00:05:02,052 --> 00:05:05,054
He's my honorary uncle, I call him Mamaji.

26
00:05:05,222 --> 00:05:07,974
My father's best friend, my swimming guru.

27
00:05:08,308 --> 00:05:11,727
I trained with him
3 times a week at the ashram.

28
00:05:11,895 --> 00:05:14,939
His lessons would save my life in the end.

29
00:05:15,607 --> 00:05:20,111
A mouthful of water
will not harm you, but panic will.

30
00:05:21,446 --> 00:05:24,615
Remember to breathe now,
don't hold your breath.

31
00:05:24,992 --> 00:05:26,450
Good boy.

32
00:05:29,913 --> 00:05:31,622
I hope you don't mind vegetarian.

33
00:05:31,790 --> 00:05:34,125
No, no. Not at all.

34
00:05:34,292 --> 00:05:36,252
And your name?
Huh?

35
00:05:36,670 --> 00:05:39,422
You were going to tell me
how you got your name, I think.

36
00:05:39,589 --> 00:05:43,592
Oh, yes. I got it from something 
Mamaji once told my father.

37
00:05:43,760 --> 00:05:45,469
You see, most travellers collect

38
00:05:45,554 --> 00:05:47,179
postcards or teacups on their journeys. . .

39
00:05:47,347 --> 00:05:48,347
but not Mamaji.

40
00:05:48,515 --> 00:05:50,599
Mamaji collects swimming pools.

41
00:05:50,767 --> 00:05:53,477
He swims in every pool he comes upon.

42
00:06:01,695 --> 00:06:03,487
One day, Mamaji said to my father that,

43
00:06:03,613 --> 00:06:05,448
of all the pools in the world...

44
00:06:05,615 --> 00:06:08,951
the most beautiful was a public pool in Paris.

45
00:06:09,119 --> 00:06:10,703
That the water there was so clear,

46
00:06:10,787 --> 00:06:12,997
you could make your morning coffee with it.

47
00:06:13,165 --> 00:06:16,500
That a single swim there changed his life.

48
00:06:30,307 --> 00:06:32,141
Before I was born, he said...

49
00:06:32,309 --> 00:06:34,894
"lf you want your son to have a clean soul...

50
00:06:35,062 --> 00:06:39,482
"you must take him one day
to swim in the Piscine Monitor."

51
00:06:39,649 --> 00:06:43,486
I never understood why my father
took this so much to heart.

52
00:06:44,154 --> 00:06:49,158
But he did, and I was named
"Piscine Molitor Patel."

53
00:06:49,993 --> 00:06:52,369
Imagine me trying to explain that name.

54
00:06:52,537 --> 00:06:55,206
I barely made it to the age of 11 before...

55
00:06:55,373 --> 00:06:57,416
Hey, Piscine!

56
00:06:58,335 --> 00:07:01,212
Are you pissing right now?

57
00:07:01,838 --> 00:07:03,380
Look at him, he's pissing!

58
00:07:03,548 --> 00:07:07,718
With one word, my name went from an elegant
French swimming pool...

59
00:07:07,886 --> 00:07:09,678
to a stinking Indian latrine.

60
00:07:09,763 --> 00:07:11,680
I was "Pissing" everywhere.

61
00:07:11,848 --> 00:07:14,517
No Pissing in the schoolyard!

62
00:07:15,894 --> 00:07:17,686
Even the teachers  started doing it.

63
00:07:17,854 --> 00:07:19,188
Not deliberately, of course.

64
00:07:19,356 --> 00:07:23,234
So, then, what might occur
if we release gas too quickly?

65
00:07:23,401 --> 00:07:24,527
Pissing?

66
00:07:25,403 --> 00:07:27,238
He said "Pissing."

67
00:07:32,702 --> 00:07:35,538
That's enough! Order! Order!

68
00:07:36,039 --> 00:07:38,791
When we returned
the next year for our first day of school,

69
00:07:38,875 --> 00:07:40,084
I was prepared.

70
00:07:40,252 --> 00:07:41,544
Present, sir.

71
00:07:42,045 --> 00:07:44,130
Piscine Patel.

72
00:07:49,553 --> 00:07:53,055
Good morning. I am Piscine Molitor Patel.

73
00:07:53,640 --> 00:07:55,224
Known to all as. . .

74
00:07:56,560 --> 00:07:59,728
Pi, the sixteenth letter of the Greek alphabet. . .

75
00:07:59,896 --> 00:08:03,566
which is also used in mathematics
to represent the ratio. . .

76
00:08:03,733 --> 00:08:07,236
of any circle's circumference to its diameter.

77
00:08:07,404 --> 00:08:09,446
An irrational number of infinite length,

78
00:08:09,573 --> 00:08:11,657
usually rounded to 3 digits. . .

79
00:08:11,825 --> 00:08:16,453
as 3.14.

80
00:08:17,080 --> 00:08:19,081
Pi.

81
00:08:20,083 --> 00:08:24,587
Very impressive, Pi. Now, sit down.

82
00:08:28,175 --> 00:08:29,758
And from then on, you were "Pi"?

83
00:08:30,343 --> 00:08:32,469
Well, no, not quite.

84
00:08:32,846 --> 00:08:34,680
Nice try, Pissing.

85
00:08:36,433 --> 00:08:38,684
But I still had the whole day ahead of me.

86
00:08:38,852 --> 00:08:40,436
French class was next.

87
00:08:40,729 --> 00:08:42,771
Je m'appelle Piscine Molitor Patel.

88
00:08:43,273 --> 00:08:44,607
Dit Pi.

89
00:08:46,818 --> 00:08:48,319
Then, geography.

90
00:08:48,486 --> 00:08:52,114
These are the first 20 decimal places of pi.

91
00:08:52,282 --> 00:08:55,284
My last class of the day was mathematics.

92
00:08:55,827 --> 00:08:59,872
Slowly, slowly, slowly.

93
00:09:04,377 --> 00:09:11,300
3. 7. 5. 8. 9.

94
00:09:11,468 --> 00:09:16,138
8. 5. 8. 9.

95
00:09:16,306 --> 00:09:19,141
It's right. He's really doing this.

96
00:09:19,309 --> 00:09:22,728
Pi! Pi! Pi!

97
00:09:22,896 --> 00:09:27,816
By the end of that day,
I was Pi Patel, school legend.

98
00:09:29,027 --> 00:09:32,571
Um, Mamaji tells me
you're a legend among sailors, too.

99
00:09:32,656 --> 00:09:33,864
Out there, all alone.

100
00:09:34,032 --> 00:09:36,200
Oh, I don't even know how to sail.

101
00:09:36,368 --> 00:09:39,495
And I wasn't alone out there.
Richard Parker was with me.

102
00:09:40,497 --> 00:09:42,373
Richard Parker?

103
00:09:42,540 --> 00:09:44,041
Mamaji didn't tell me everything.

104
00:09:44,209 --> 00:09:47,044
He just said I should look you up 
when I got back to Montreal.

105
00:09:47,212 --> 00:09:49,046
So, what were you doing in Pondicherry?

106
00:09:50,423 --> 00:09:52,341
Writing a novel.

107
00:09:52,509 --> 00:09:54,343
By the way, I enjoyed your first book.

108
00:09:55,220 --> 00:09:57,012
So, this new one, is it set in India?

109
00:09:57,180 --> 00:10:00,683
No, Portugal, actually.
But it's cheaper living in India.

110
00:10:02,269 --> 00:10:05,437
Ah, well, I look forward to reading it.

111
00:10:05,522 --> 00:10:06,563
You can't.

112
00:10:07,357 --> 00:10:08,941
I threw it out.

113
00:10:09,109 --> 00:10:10,859
2 years trying to bring this thing to life. . .

114
00:10:11,027 --> 00:10:14,947
and then one day,
it sputtered, coughed and died.

115
00:10:16,241 --> 00:10:17,616
Oh, I'm sorry.

116
00:10:19,077 --> 00:10:22,955
Uh, I was sitting in this coffee house in
Pondicherry one afternoon,

117
00:10:23,039 --> 00:10:24,164
mourning my loss. . .

118
00:10:24,249 --> 00:10:28,085
when this old man at the table next to me
struck up a conversation.

119
00:10:28,211 --> 00:10:29,920
Yeah, Mamaji, he does that.

120
00:10:30,088 --> 00:10:31,922
When I told him about my 
abandoned book, he said. . .

121
00:10:32,090 --> 00:10:34,300
"So, a Canadian who's come to French India

122
00:10:34,384 --> 00:10:36,051
"in search of a story."

123
00:10:36,219 --> 00:10:39,263
"Well, my friend, I know an 
Indian in French Canada. . .

124
00:10:39,431 --> 00:10:42,224
"with the most incredible story to tell.

125
00:10:42,392 --> 00:10:46,562
"It must be fate that the 2 of you should meet."

126
00:10:49,733 --> 00:10:53,110
Well, I haven't spoken
about Richard Parker in so many years.

127
00:10:53,278 --> 00:10:55,904
So, what has Mamaji already told you?

128
00:10:56,072 --> 00:10:59,658
He said you had a story
that would make me believe in God.

129
00:10:59,826 --> 00:11:03,245
He would say that about a nice meal.

130
00:11:04,664 --> 00:11:07,249
As for God, I can only tell you my story.

131
00:11:08,752 --> 00:11:11,086
You will decide for yourself what you believe.

132
00:11:11,254 --> 00:11:12,921
Fair enough.

133
00:11:13,673 --> 00:11:16,008
Let's see, then. Where to begin?

134
00:11:17,010 --> 00:11:21,305
Pondicherry is the French Riviera of India.

135
00:11:25,352 --> 00:11:27,394
In the streets closest to the ocean,

136
00:11:27,479 --> 00:11:30,189
you might think you were in the south of France.

137
00:11:32,984 --> 00:11:35,778
A few blocks inland, there's a canal.

138
00:11:35,945 --> 00:11:38,280
Just beyond that is Indian Pondicherry.

139
00:11:39,282 --> 00:11:42,826
And the Muslim quarter is just to the west.

140
00:11:42,994 --> 00:11:46,455
When the French handed Pondicherry
back to us in 1954. . .

141
00:11:46,623 --> 00:11:50,125
the town decided that some sort 
of commemoration was in order.

142
00:11:50,502 --> 00:11:54,129
My father, who was a clever
 businessman, came up with one.

143
00:11:54,297 --> 00:11:57,716
He ran a hotel, and he got
the idea to open a zoo...

144
00:11:57,884 --> 00:12:00,677
in the local botanical gardens instead.

145
00:12:02,972 --> 00:12:07,017
As it also happened, my mother was
a botanist in the gardens.

146
00:12:07,185 --> 00:12:11,897
They met, married, and a year later
my brother Ravi was born.

147
00:12:12,065 --> 00:12:14,233
I came 2 years after that.

148
00:12:14,984 --> 00:12:18,404
It sounds magical, growing up in. . .

149
00:12:24,160 --> 00:12:25,536
Amen.

150
00:12:26,329 --> 00:12:28,163
Yeah, let's eat.

151
00:12:28,498 --> 00:12:30,165
I didn't know Hindus said "amen."

152
00:12:30,333 --> 00:12:31,667
Catholic Hindus do.

153
00:12:31,835 --> 00:12:32,918
Catholic Hindus?

154
00:12:33,002 --> 00:12:37,005
We get to feel guiIty before hundreds
 of gods, instead of just one.

155
00:12:38,049 --> 00:12:40,426
But you're a Hindu first?

156
00:12:40,593 --> 00:12:43,554
None of us knows God 
until someone introduces us.

157
00:12:43,721 --> 00:12:46,515
I was first introduced to God as a Hindu.

158
00:12:46,683 --> 00:12:49,268
There are 33 million gods in the Hindu religion.

159
00:12:49,436 --> 00:12:51,520
How can I not come to know a few of them?

160
00:12:53,273 --> 00:12:56,275
I met Krishna first.

161
00:12:58,236 --> 00:13:00,237
Yashoda once accused baby Krishna of eating dirt.

162
00:13:01,030 --> 00:13:05,075
"Tut, tut you naughty boy you shouldn't do that."

163
00:13:05,493 --> 00:13:08,287
But he didn't!

164
00:13:09,372 --> 00:13:10,831
That's what he told her .

165
00:13:10,957 --> 00:13:12,916
"I didn't eat dirt."

166
00:13:13,626 --> 00:13:16,712
Yashoda said, "No? Well then..."

167
00:13:16,921 --> 00:13:19,047
"Open your  mouth."

168
00:13:19,215 --> 00:13:21,967
So Krishna opened his mouth.

169
00:13:22,135 --> 00:13:24,136
And what do you think Yashoda saw?

170
00:13:24,220 --> 00:13:25,429
What?

171
00:13:26,222 --> 00:13:33,812
She saw in Krishna's mouth
the whole entire universe.

172
00:14:01,090 --> 00:14:04,134
The gods were my superheroes growing up.

173
00:14:04,302 --> 00:14:06,595
Hanuman, the monkey god...

174
00:14:06,763 --> 00:14:10,599
lifting an entire mountain
to save his friend Lakshman.

175
00:14:10,767 --> 00:14:13,101
Ganesh, the elephant-headed...

176
00:14:13,269 --> 00:14:17,523
risking his life to defend the honor
of his mother, Parvati.

177
00:14:17,774 --> 00:14:22,778
Vishnu, the supreme soul, the source of all things.

178
00:14:23,363 --> 00:14:26,865
Vishnu sleeps, floating
on the shoreless cosmic ocean...

179
00:14:27,033 --> 00:14:29,952
and we are the stuff of his dreaming.

180
00:14:31,454 --> 00:14:33,330
Spectacle.

181
00:14:33,790 --> 00:14:37,793
Don't let these stories
and pretty lights fool you, boys.

182
00:14:37,961 --> 00:14:42,047
Religion is darkness.

183
00:14:44,384 --> 00:14:47,844
My dear appa believed
himself part of the new India.

184
00:14:48,680 --> 00:14:50,973
As a child, he had had polio.

185
00:14:51,140 --> 00:14:55,352
He used to lie in bed racked with pain,
wondering where God was.

186
00:14:56,187 --> 00:15:00,357
In the end, God didn't save him,
Western medicine did.

187
00:15:03,653 --> 00:15:05,153
My amma went to college...

188
00:15:05,321 --> 00:15:08,156
and thought her family
was part of the new India as well...

189
00:15:08,324 --> 00:15:09,992
until her parents cut her off...

190
00:15:10,159 --> 00:15:12,536
because they thought
she was marrying beneath her.

191
00:15:13,663 --> 00:15:17,416
Her religion was the only link she had to her past.

192
00:15:27,051 --> 00:15:30,721
I met Christ in the mountains when I was 12.

193
00:15:30,888 --> 00:15:34,600
We were visiting relatives,
tea growers in Munnar.

194
00:15:34,767 --> 00:15:39,021
It was our third day there.
Ravi and I were terribly bored.

195
00:15:39,188 --> 00:15:42,107
Challenge. I'll give you 2 rupees.

196
00:15:42,275 --> 00:15:45,444
Run in to that church and drink the holy water.

197
00:16:24,609 --> 00:16:26,193
You must be thirsty.

198
00:16:29,656 --> 00:16:31,448
Here.

199
00:16:31,616 --> 00:16:33,408
I brought you this.

200
00:16:48,591 --> 00:16:51,468
Why would a god do that?

201
00:16:51,636 --> 00:16:53,762
Why would He send His own son. . .

202
00:16:53,930 --> 00:16:57,307
to suffer for the sins of ordinary people?

203
00:16:57,475 --> 00:16:59,434
Because He loves us.

204
00:17:00,186 --> 00:17:02,813
God made Himself approachable to us,

205
00:17:02,939 --> 00:17:05,607
human, so we could understand Him.

206
00:17:05,775 --> 00:17:08,360
We can't understand God in all His perfection.

207
00:17:08,528 --> 00:17:11,113
But we can understand God's son

208
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:13,865
and His suffering as we would a brother's.

209
00:17:14,117 --> 00:17:16,326
That made no sense.

210
00:17:16,494 --> 00:17:20,956
Sacrificing the innocent
to atone for the sins of the guilty. . .

211
00:17:21,124 --> 00:17:23,125
What kind of love is that?

212
00:17:25,795 --> 00:17:27,629
But this son...

213
00:17:27,797 --> 00:17:29,297
I couldn't get him out of my head.

214
00:17:32,468 --> 00:17:35,470
If God is so perfect and we are not...

215
00:17:35,888 --> 00:17:38,682
why would He want to create all this?

216
00:17:38,850 --> 00:17:41,226
Why does he need us at all?

217
00:17:41,394 --> 00:17:44,521
All you have to know is that He loves us.

218
00:17:44,981 --> 00:17:47,899
God so loved this world
that He gave His only son.

219
00:17:48,067 --> 00:17:50,026
The longer I listened to the priest...

220
00:17:50,194 --> 00:17:53,196
the more I came to like this son of God.

221
00:17:53,364 --> 00:17:57,325
Thank you, Vishnu, for introducing me to Christ.

222
00:18:04,876 --> 00:18:07,127
I came to faith through Hinduism

223
00:18:07,253 --> 00:18:09,504
and I found God's love through Christ.

224
00:18:09,672 --> 00:18:12,174
But God wasn't finished with me yet.

225
00:18:22,268 --> 00:18:24,853
God works in mysterious ways.

226
00:18:25,021 --> 00:18:27,522
And so it was, He introduced Himself again.

227
00:18:27,857 --> 00:18:30,400
This time by the name of Allah.

228
00:18:46,083 --> 00:18:47,709
Allahu Akbar.

229
00:18:50,254 --> 00:18:52,547
My Arabic was never very good...

230
00:18:52,715 --> 00:18:56,384
but the sound and feel of the words
brought me closer to God.

231
00:18:56,552 --> 00:18:57,761
In performing Salah...

232
00:18:57,929 --> 00:19:00,096
the ground I touched became holy ground...

233
00:19:00,264 --> 00:19:03,725
and I found a feeling
of serenity and brotherhood.

234
00:19:13,444 --> 00:19:16,071
This lamb is exquisite.

235
00:19:16,572 --> 00:19:18,782
It's the best dish on the table.

236
00:19:19,242 --> 00:19:20,951
You're all missing out.

237
00:19:22,411 --> 00:19:25,580
You only need to convert
to 3 more religions, Piscine. . .

238
00:19:25,748 --> 00:19:28,917
and you will spend your life on holiday.

239
00:19:29,168 --> 00:19:32,420
Are you going to Mecca this year, Swami Jesus?

240
00:19:32,588 --> 00:19:35,841
Or to Rome for your coronation as Pope Pi-us?

241
00:19:36,092 --> 00:19:37,759
You stay out of this, Ravi.

242
00:19:37,927 --> 00:19:40,011
Just as you like cricket, Pi has his own interests.

243
00:19:40,179 --> 00:19:42,430
No, Gita, Ravi has a point.

244
00:19:42,807 --> 00:19:47,143
You cannot follow 3 different religions
at the same time, Piscine.

245
00:19:47,311 --> 00:19:48,603
Why not?

246
00:19:48,771 --> 00:19:52,357
Because believing in everything
at the same time. . .

247
00:19:52,525 --> 00:19:55,777
is the same as not believing in anything at all.

248
00:19:55,945 --> 00:19:59,114
He's young, Santosh. He's still finding his way.

249
00:19:59,282 --> 00:20:02,701
And how can he find his way
if he does not choose a path?

250
00:20:03,452 --> 00:20:07,831
Listen, instead of leaping
from one religion to the next. . .

251
00:20:07,999 --> 00:20:10,000
why not start with reason?

252
00:20:10,710 --> 00:20:12,002
In a few hundred years. . .

253
00:20:12,169 --> 00:20:14,880
science has taken us farther 
in understanding the universe. . .

254
00:20:15,047 --> 00:20:17,799
than religion has in 10,000.

255
00:20:19,552 --> 00:20:21,344
That is true.

256
00:20:21,512 --> 00:20:22,804
Your father is right.

257
00:20:23,514 --> 00:20:26,516
Science can teach us more 
about what is out there. . .

258
00:20:26,684 --> 00:20:28,476
but not what is in here.

259
00:20:29,645 --> 00:20:32,188
Some eat meat, some eat vegetable.

260
00:20:32,356 --> 00:20:34,691
I do not expect us all
to agree about everything. . .

261
00:20:34,859 --> 00:20:36,693
but I would much rather have you

262
00:20:36,777 --> 00:20:38,528
believe in something I don't agree with. . .

263
00:20:38,696 --> 00:20:41,489
than to accept everything blindly.

264
00:20:41,657 --> 00:20:45,493
And that begins with thinking rationally.

265
00:20:46,871 --> 00:20:48,663
Do you understand?

266
00:20:51,083 --> 00:20:52,542
Good.

267
00:20:58,507 --> 00:21:00,425
I would like to be baptized.

268
00:21:07,058 --> 00:21:09,434
So, you're a Christian and a Muslim?

269
00:21:09,602 --> 00:21:11,019
And a Hindu, of course.

270
00:21:11,187 --> 00:21:12,354
And a Jew, I suppose.

271
00:21:12,521 --> 00:21:15,523
Well, I do teach a course
on the Kabbalah at the university.

272
00:21:15,691 --> 00:21:18,360
And why not?
Faith is a house with many rooms.

273
00:21:18,527 --> 00:21:20,111
But no room for doubt?

274
00:21:20,279 --> 00:21:21,947
Oh, plenty. On every floor.

275
00:21:22,114 --> 00:21:23,531
Doubt is useful.

276
00:21:23,699 --> 00:21:25,742
It keeps faith a living thing.

277
00:21:25,910 --> 00:21:28,078
After all, you cannot know
the strength of your faith

278
00:21:28,162 --> 00:21:29,371
until it's been tested.

279
00:21:33,459 --> 00:21:36,211
Where's Selvam?
We shouldn't be in here without him.

280
00:21:36,379 --> 00:21:37,879
Stop worrying.

281
00:21:39,548 --> 00:21:42,384
I have seen him do this a thousand times.

282
00:21:44,887 --> 00:21:47,764
I want to meet our new tiger.

283
00:21:48,766 --> 00:21:49,808
Pi!

284
00:21:49,892 --> 00:21:52,560
Hello? Richard Parker?

285
00:21:52,937 --> 00:21:55,939
A tiger? Richard Parker was a tiger?

286
00:21:56,107 --> 00:21:58,942
Yeah, he got his name through a clerical error.

287
00:21:59,110 --> 00:22:02,112
A hunter caught him drinking from 
a stream when he was a cub. . .

288
00:22:02,279 --> 00:22:04,072
and named him Thirsty.

289
00:22:04,240 --> 00:22:07,242
When Thirsty got too big,
the hunter sold him to our zoo. . .

290
00:22:07,410 --> 00:22:10,245
but the names got switched on the paperwork.

291
00:22:10,997 --> 00:22:12,872
The hunter was listed as Thirsty,

292
00:22:12,957 --> 00:22:14,833
and the tiger was called Richard Parker.

293
00:22:15,418 --> 00:22:18,628
We laughed about it, and the name stuck.

294
00:22:19,005 --> 00:22:20,505
Let's go. . .

295
00:22:21,257 --> 00:22:23,466
before we get into trouble.

296
00:22:23,634 --> 00:22:25,468
I want to see him close up.

297
00:22:25,636 --> 00:22:27,095
You're not a zookeeper.

298
00:22:27,513 --> 00:22:29,097
Come on!

299
00:22:47,450 --> 00:22:49,617
That's it, Richard Parker.

300
00:22:49,785 --> 00:22:51,494
It's for you.

301
00:23:20,983 --> 00:23:21,983
No!

302
00:23:23,194 --> 00:23:25,320
What are you thinking?

303
00:23:25,821 --> 00:23:27,155
Are you out of your mind?

304
00:23:27,323 --> 00:23:29,365
Who gave you permission to come back here?

305
00:23:29,533 --> 00:23:32,911
You have just ignored everything
I've ever taught you.

306
00:23:33,662 --> 00:23:36,247
I just wanted to say hello to him.

307
00:23:36,707 --> 00:23:38,500
You think that tiger is your friend?

308
00:23:38,667 --> 00:23:41,002
He's an animal, not a playmate.

309
00:23:42,171 --> 00:23:44,339
Animals have souls.

310
00:23:44,507 --> 00:23:46,841
I have seen it in their eyes.

311
00:23:49,720 --> 00:23:51,096
Find Selvam.

312
00:24:02,024 --> 00:24:04,776
You're  sure , Sir? Pi's just a boy.

313
00:24:04,860 --> 00:24:06,861
Do it. Go ahead!

314
00:24:07,863 --> 00:24:10,532
Animals do not think like we do.

315
00:24:10,699 --> 00:24:13,535
People who forget that get themselves killed.

316
00:24:13,702 --> 00:24:17,872
That tiger is not your friend.

317
00:24:18,040 --> 00:24:19,541
When you look into his eyes. . .

318
00:24:19,708 --> 00:24:23,128
you are seeing your own emotions
reflected back at you.

319
00:24:23,295 --> 00:24:25,046
Nothing else.

320
00:24:25,381 --> 00:24:27,132
Don't be stupid. Say you're sorry.

321
00:24:28,884 --> 00:24:30,760
What have you done, Piscine?

322
00:24:30,928 --> 00:24:33,221
You know what your father
 said about coming back here.

323
00:24:33,889 --> 00:24:37,225
I am sorry. I was. . .

324
00:24:37,726 --> 00:24:39,144
What are you thinking?

325
00:24:39,311 --> 00:24:41,062
This is between a father and his sons.

326
00:24:42,940 --> 00:24:44,315
He said he's sorry.

327
00:24:44,483 --> 00:24:45,942
You want to scar them for life?

328
00:24:46,110 --> 00:24:49,070
Scar them? That boy almost lost his arm.

329
00:24:49,238 --> 00:24:50,572
But he's still a boy.

330
00:24:50,739 --> 00:24:52,448
He will be a man sooner than you think.

331
00:24:52,616 --> 00:24:55,577
And this is a lesson
I do not want them ever to forget.

332
00:24:56,328 --> 00:24:57,745
Selvam!

333
00:25:45,836 --> 00:25:48,671
. ..and so has placed the country
in a state of emergency.

334
00:25:48,839 --> 00:25:52,133
Under the directive,
the states of Gujarat and Tamil Nadu...

335
00:25:52,301 --> 00:25:55,345
will be placed under the direct 
authority of the central government.

336
00:25:55,512 --> 00:25:57,222
Police will be granted powers...

337
00:25:57,389 --> 00:25:59,724
to arrest and indefinitely detain citizens

338
00:25:59,808 --> 00:26:01,517
responsible for the uprising.

339
00:26:06,065 --> 00:26:09,817
Things changed after the day of Appa's lesson.

340
00:26:09,985 --> 00:26:12,654
The world had lost some of its enchantment.

341
00:26:13,155 --> 00:26:16,824
School was a bore.
Nothing but facts, fractions and French.

342
00:26:17,368 --> 00:26:21,412
Words and patterns
that went on and on, without end.

343
00:26:21,580 --> 00:26:24,082
Just likem my irrational nickname.

344
00:26:29,004 --> 00:26:31,547
I grew restless searching for something

345
00:26:31,674 --> 00:26:34,259
that might bring meaning back into my life.

346
00:26:35,427 --> 00:26:38,096
And then, I met Anandi.

347
00:26:47,064 --> 00:26:48,856
Mother made me study music.

348
00:26:49,024 --> 00:26:51,442
And one day, my teacher came down with the flu.

349
00:26:52,027 --> 00:26:53,736
He asked if I could take his place,

350
00:26:53,821 --> 00:26:55,613
playing rhythms for a dance class.

351
00:27:11,880 --> 00:27:13,089
No.

352
00:27:13,590 --> 00:27:15,216
lf you do not concentrate. . .

353
00:27:15,384 --> 00:27:18,761
you cannot express
your love of God through dance.

354
00:27:18,929 --> 00:27:21,055
Feel the ground beneath your feet.

355
00:27:21,223 --> 00:27:23,725
Open your gaze out onto the horizon.

356
00:27:23,892 --> 00:27:28,438
Let that spiritual energy
pulse through you and out into the world.

357
00:27:28,647 --> 00:27:30,565
Through abhinaya.

358
00:27:31,233 --> 00:27:33,818
Anandi, come to the front. Lead them.

359
00:28:18,614 --> 00:28:20,615
Why are you following me?

360
00:28:20,783 --> 00:28:21,866
What?

361
00:28:22,284 --> 00:28:24,660
You were following me.

362
00:28:27,039 --> 00:28:29,123
What does this mean?

363
00:28:30,501 --> 00:28:33,211
In the dance, you went from pataka...

364
00:28:33,796 --> 00:28:35,838
which means the forest.

365
00:28:36,006 --> 00:28:38,800
And then you did. . .

366
00:28:40,010 --> 00:28:41,344
samputa...

367
00:28:41,512 --> 00:28:44,180
which means something that is hidden.

368
00:28:44,348 --> 00:28:45,973
And after that, you did this.

369
00:28:47,726 --> 00:28:50,186
And then you did chatura.

370
00:28:50,354 --> 00:28:53,898
But at the very end, you did this.

371
00:28:54,900 --> 00:28:57,318
None of the other dancers did that.

372
00:28:58,028 --> 00:29:00,655
What did you mean?
The god of love is hiding in the forest?

373
00:29:00,823 --> 00:29:03,658
No, that also means the lotus flower.

374
00:29:04,201 --> 00:29:06,494
Lotus flower is hiding in the forest?

375
00:29:07,663 --> 00:29:10,415
Why would a lotus flower hide in the forest?

376
00:29:18,340 --> 00:29:20,425
And this is Richard Parker.

377
00:29:21,009 --> 00:29:22,802
He is the most magnificent creature

378
00:29:22,886 --> 00:29:24,512
we've ever had here.

379
00:29:25,347 --> 00:29:27,682
Look at the way he's turning his head.

380
00:29:29,726 --> 00:29:32,895
Showing off. Like a dancer.

381
00:29:33,063 --> 00:29:35,356
No, he heard something.

382
00:29:37,359 --> 00:29:40,319
He's listening, you see?

383
00:29:49,872 --> 00:29:51,873
We have talked about it for some time.

384
00:29:52,040 --> 00:29:54,208
Do you understand what I'm saying?

385
00:29:54,376 --> 00:29:55,710
Pi?

386
00:29:56,962 --> 00:29:58,713
Sorry, you've been. . .

387
00:29:58,881 --> 00:30:00,423
Worried.

388
00:30:00,591 --> 00:30:02,383
For my family.

389
00:30:02,551 --> 00:30:05,553
Our animals are worth
far more abroad than here in India.

390
00:30:05,721 --> 00:30:07,722
And if the town council stops supporting us. . .

391
00:30:07,890 --> 00:30:09,724
I don't know where we will be.

392
00:30:09,892 --> 00:30:12,268
So, it is what we have to do.

393
00:30:13,228 --> 00:30:15,146
Do you understand?

394
00:30:17,232 --> 00:30:19,233
I'm sorry, what are we talking about?

395
00:30:19,818 --> 00:30:21,819
We are leaving India.

396
00:30:23,280 --> 00:30:24,655
What?

397
00:30:26,575 --> 00:30:28,242
We are selling the zoo.

398
00:30:29,244 --> 00:30:32,121
The zoo was never ours to sell.
The land belongs to the town.

399
00:30:32,289 --> 00:30:34,415
But the animals are ours and if we sell them. . .

400
00:30:34,583 --> 00:30:36,667
we will have enough to start a new life.

401
00:30:36,835 --> 00:30:40,087
But where would we go? Our life is here, Appa.

402
00:30:40,255 --> 00:30:41,255
Canada.

403
00:30:41,423 --> 00:30:44,091
I have some opportunities for work in Winnipeg.

404
00:30:44,259 --> 00:30:47,261
l'll be shipping most of the animals
for sale in North America.

405
00:30:47,429 --> 00:30:49,972
We can get freighter passage
for the whole family.

406
00:30:50,098 --> 00:30:51,599
So. . .

407
00:30:51,767 --> 00:30:53,351
It is settled.

408
00:30:53,519 --> 00:30:56,270
We will sail like Columbus.

409
00:30:56,855 --> 00:30:59,524
But Columbus was looking for India.

410
00:31:08,116 --> 00:31:10,868
It takes a Iot of work to sell a zoo.

411
00:31:11,620 --> 00:31:12,703
Before we Ieft...

412
00:31:12,788 --> 00:31:16,499
Anandi and I had time enough
to break each other's hearts.

413
00:31:16,959 --> 00:31:20,336
Of course, I promised
I would come back one day.

414
00:31:21,171 --> 00:31:22,672
It's funny.

415
00:31:22,839 --> 00:31:25,967
I remember everything else about our last day.

416
00:31:26,134 --> 00:31:29,220
But I don't remember saying goodbye.

417
00:31:37,646 --> 00:31:41,190
Pi? They're serving dinner below.

418
00:31:54,329 --> 00:31:55,997
Piscine. . .

419
00:31:56,164 --> 00:31:58,666
you have a whole life ahead of you.

420
00:31:59,418 --> 00:32:02,003
We are doing this for you and Ravi.

421
00:32:04,256 --> 00:32:06,382
Come inside and have some dinner.

422
00:32:15,892 --> 00:32:17,685
Vegetarian, please.

423
00:32:19,021 --> 00:32:21,897
Oh, my sons and I are vegetarians.
Do you have anything. . .

424
00:32:22,065 --> 00:32:25,192
No, no, no. Not more gravy.

425
00:32:25,360 --> 00:32:27,111
You don't want gravy? No.

426
00:32:28,363 --> 00:32:30,239
No, I want something vegetarian.

427
00:32:31,074 --> 00:32:32,575
Oh.

428
00:32:34,494 --> 00:32:35,703
Pas de probleme.

429
00:32:37,539 --> 00:32:41,250
She asked if you have some thing vegetarian.

430
00:32:43,712 --> 00:32:46,047
The cow that produced this liver was vegetarian,

431
00:32:46,214 --> 00:32:49,133
the pigs that went into
these sausages were vegetarian.

432
00:32:49,217 --> 00:32:50,593
Very funny.

433
00:32:51,219 --> 00:32:54,055
But my wife doesn't eat liver .

434
00:32:56,600 --> 00:32:58,517
Pas de probleme.

435
00:32:58,894 --> 00:33:02,480
Then she can eat the sausage,
the rice, and the gravy.

436
00:33:02,981 --> 00:33:04,982
Or you can cook your own food.

437
00:33:05,317 --> 00:33:07,818
How dare you talk to my wife like that?

438
00:33:08,487 --> 00:33:10,279
Here's your rice.

439
00:33:11,948 --> 00:33:14,075
I cook for sailors...

440
00:33:14,159 --> 00:33:15,743
not curry-eaters.

441
00:33:16,662 --> 00:33:17,411
What did you say?

442
00:33:17,621 --> 00:33:18,454
Let go of me!

443
00:33:18,538 --> 00:33:22,124
Who do you think you are?
You're nothing but a servant!

444
00:33:22,209 --> 00:33:24,752
I feed people! You feed monkeys!

445
00:33:33,428 --> 00:33:34,929
Hello.

446
00:33:35,097 --> 00:33:36,639
I am happy Buddhist.

447
00:33:36,973 --> 00:33:38,599
So, I eat rice

448
00:33:38,684 --> 00:33:40,601
next to gravy.

449
00:33:40,936 --> 00:33:44,313
On ship, gravy is not meat.

450
00:33:44,481 --> 00:33:45,648
Is taste.

451
00:33:46,358 --> 00:33:47,692
You try?

452
00:34:10,507 --> 00:34:12,383
Don't worry.

453
00:34:12,551 --> 00:34:17,680
We will have plenty of fresh supplies
after we stop in Manila.

454
00:34:19,516 --> 00:34:23,144
Why give Orange Juice tranquilizers?

455
00:34:23,311 --> 00:34:26,230
She's not going to cause any trouble.

456
00:34:26,398 --> 00:34:29,358
The stress of traveling
is not good for the animals. . .

457
00:34:29,526 --> 00:34:32,319
and it helps with the seasickness.

458
00:34:33,488 --> 00:34:39,660
We don't want to be cleaning up
after a seasick orangutan. . .

459
00:34:40,245 --> 00:34:41,495
do we?

460
00:34:47,919 --> 00:34:50,045
My father was a businessman.

461
00:34:50,130 --> 00:34:52,548
He had never tended the animals himseIf.

462
00:34:54,384 --> 00:34:55,426
I realized. . .

463
00:34:55,594 --> 00:34:59,555
leaving India must have been 
harder for him than it was for me.

464
00:35:05,437 --> 00:35:06,771
So. . .

465
00:35:07,230 --> 00:35:09,398
Have I forgotten anything?

466
00:35:09,566 --> 00:35:10,691
I think you've set the stage.

467
00:35:10,859 --> 00:35:14,236
So far, we have an Indian boy
named after a French swimming pool. . .

468
00:35:14,404 --> 00:35:17,698
on a Japanese ship full of 
animals, heading to Canada.

469
00:35:17,866 --> 00:35:19,116
Yes.

470
00:35:19,284 --> 00:35:23,037
Now, we have to send our boy
into the middle of the Pacific and--

471
00:35:23,205 --> 00:35:26,207
And make me believe in God.

472
00:35:27,584 --> 00:35:29,084
Yeah.

473
00:35:29,252 --> 00:35:31,128
We'll get there.

474
00:35:36,468 --> 00:35:38,761
It was 4 days out of Manila. . .

475
00:35:38,929 --> 00:35:42,056
above the Mariana Trench, the deepest spot on Earth.

476
00:35:45,727 --> 00:35:48,687
Our ship, The Tsimtsum, pushed on,

477
00:35:48,814 --> 00:35:51,816
bullishly indifferent to its surroundings.

478
00:35:52,776 --> 00:35:57,154
It moved with the slow,
massive confidence of a continent.

479
00:36:33,608 --> 00:36:34,817
Ravi?

480
00:36:35,610 --> 00:36:36,944
Did you hear that, Ravi?

481
00:36:37,112 --> 00:36:38,320
I'm sleeping.

482
00:36:38,488 --> 00:36:40,489
It's a thunderstorm. Let's go watch.

483
00:36:40,657 --> 00:36:41,949
Are you crazy?

484
00:36:42,367 --> 00:36:44,201
We will get hit by lightning.

485
00:36:44,452 --> 00:36:47,288
No, we won't. It will hit the bridge first.

486
00:36:48,790 --> 00:36:51,166
Don't tempt a storm, Pi.

487
00:37:04,639 --> 00:37:05,931
Whoa.

488
00:37:19,529 --> 00:37:20,654
Oh!

489
00:37:55,106 --> 00:37:58,943
More rain! More rain!

490
00:38:01,488 --> 00:38:03,948
Lord of Storms!

491
00:38:04,240 --> 00:38:05,574
Whoa!

492
00:38:06,451 --> 00:38:07,993
Lightning!

493
00:38:26,054 --> 00:38:27,054
Ah!

494
00:38:47,617 --> 00:38:49,076
Amma!

495
00:38:50,412 --> 00:38:51,495
Appa!

496
00:38:53,081 --> 00:38:56,792
Ravi! Get out! Get out!

497
00:39:34,456 --> 00:39:36,415
Help me!

498
00:39:41,629 --> 00:39:42,963
Help!

499
00:39:45,175 --> 00:39:46,467
Get in the boat!

500
00:39:46,634 --> 00:39:48,635
Please! Save my family!

501
00:39:48,803 --> 00:39:50,596
Don't scare, okay? Wait, stay here!

502
00:39:50,764 --> 00:39:52,347
You have to help them! Please!

503
00:39:52,515 --> 00:39:53,807
Put this on.

504
00:39:53,975 --> 00:39:56,393
No, no, my family! Please!

505
00:39:58,730 --> 00:40:00,147
We have to help them!

506
00:40:00,315 --> 00:40:02,608
We don't have time. My family's back there!

507
00:40:02,776 --> 00:40:05,027
We help! You must go!

508
00:40:05,195 --> 00:40:06,361
Who let all the animals out?

509
00:40:06,529 --> 00:40:07,780
You have to go now!

510
00:40:07,947 --> 00:40:10,240
No, wait, my father! He can't swim!

511
00:40:10,325 --> 00:40:11,366
Go!

512
00:40:14,287 --> 00:40:17,247
Hang on to the boat! Hold, hold!

513
00:40:18,500 --> 00:40:20,084
Bring it down!

514
00:40:28,009 --> 00:40:31,011
Hey! You! What are you doing?

515
00:40:32,639 --> 00:40:33,680
Jump!

516
00:40:34,057 --> 00:40:36,058
Hey, hey!

517
00:41:39,038 --> 00:41:43,458
Hey! Over here! Over here!

518
00:42:18,119 --> 00:42:19,828
Richard Parker?

519
00:42:19,996 --> 00:42:21,663
No! No!

520
00:42:22,582 --> 00:42:25,751
No! Go away! Go away!

521
00:44:14,736 --> 00:44:16,236
Agh!

522
00:44:34,839 --> 00:44:37,716
Amma!

523
00:44:37,884 --> 00:44:41,845
Appa! Ravi.

