But what always hurts the most. . .

786
01:46:53,657 --> 01:46:57,285
is not taking a moment to say goodbye.

787
01:46:58,996 --> 01:47:03,166
I was never able to thank my father
for all I learned from him.

788
01:47:03,334 --> 01:47:06,336
To tell him, without his lessons. . .

789
01:47:06,921 --> 01:47:09,172
I would never have survived.

790
01:47:11,300 --> 01:47:14,969
I know Richard Parker is a tiger,
but I wish I had said. . .

791
01:47:15,137 --> 01:47:17,806
"It's over. We survived.

792
01:47:17,973 --> 01:47:21,768
"Thank you for saving my life.
I love you, Richard Parker.

793
01:47:21,936 --> 01:47:24,646
"You will always be with me.

794
01:47:26,190 --> 01:47:28,525
"May God be with you."

795
01:47:35,699 --> 01:47:38,034
I don't know what to say.

796
01:47:44,375 --> 01:47:46,960
It's hard to believe, isn't it?

797
01:47:49,964 --> 01:47:52,173
It is a lot to take in.

798
01:47:52,550 --> 01:47:55,301
To figure out what it all means.

799
01:47:55,469 --> 01:47:56,636
lf it happened, it happened.

800
01:47:56,720 --> 01:47:59,305
Why should it have to mean anything?

801
01:48:00,850 --> 01:48:03,810
Some of it is pretty incredible.

802
01:48:03,978 --> 01:48:06,312
See, I was the only one
who survived the shipwreck.

803
01:48:06,897 --> 01:48:10,066
So the Japanese shipping company 
sent 2 men to talk to me. . .

804
01:48:10,234 --> 01:48:13,069
in the Mexican hospital where I was recovering.

805
01:48:15,156 --> 01:48:17,073
I still have a copy of their report.

806
01:48:19,243 --> 01:48:22,328
They had insurance claims to settle. . .

807
01:48:22,496 --> 01:48:25,415
and they wanted to find out why the ship sank.

808
01:48:26,417 --> 01:48:27,876
They didn't believe me, either.

809
01:48:31,172 --> 01:48:34,841
Thousands of meerkats
on a floating carnivorous island. . .

810
01:48:35,009 --> 01:48:36,926
and no one has ever seen it?

811
01:48:37,094 --> 01:48:39,888
Yes, just like I told you.

812
01:48:40,055 --> 01:48:41,764
Bananas don't float.

813
01:48:41,932 --> 01:48:43,433
Why are you talking about bananas?

814
01:48:43,601 --> 01:48:46,269
You said the orangutan floated 
to you on a bundle of bananas.

815
01:48:46,437 --> 01:48:48,271
But bananas don't float.

816
01:48:48,439 --> 01:48:49,772
Are you sure about that?

817
01:48:49,940 --> 01:48:52,442
Of course they do. Try it for yourself.

818
01:48:53,402 --> 01:48:57,572
In any case, we are not here
to talk about bananas or meerkats.

819
01:48:57,740 --> 01:49:01,075
Look, I've just told you a long story
and I'm very tired.

820
01:49:01,243 --> 01:49:06,122
We are here because
a Japanese cargo ship sank in the Pacific.

821
01:49:06,290 --> 01:49:08,750
Something I never forget.

822
01:49:09,919 --> 01:49:12,378
I lost my whole family.

823
01:49:17,134 --> 01:49:18,801
Get him somewater.

824
01:49:21,263 --> 01:49:23,473
We don't mean to push you.

825
01:49:24,558 --> 01:49:27,435
And you have our deepest sympathies.

826
01:49:27,603 --> 01:49:29,604
But we have come a long way. . .

827
01:49:29,772 --> 01:49:32,941
and we are no closer to 
understanding why the ship sank.

828
01:49:33,108 --> 01:49:35,235
Because I don't know.

829
01:49:35,402 --> 01:49:36,945
I was asleep. Something woke me up.

830
01:49:37,112 --> 01:49:39,656
It could have been an explosion,
I can't be sure.

831
01:49:39,823 --> 01:49:41,741
And then the ship sank.

832
01:49:42,284 --> 01:49:43,952
What else do you want from me?

833
01:49:44,119 --> 01:49:46,412
A story that won't make us look like fools.

834
01:49:46,580 --> 01:49:49,582
We need a simpler story for our report.

835
01:49:49,750 --> 01:49:51,918
One our company can understand.

836
01:49:52,169 --> 01:49:54,671
A story we can all believe.

837
01:49:57,508 --> 01:50:00,510
So, a story without things you've never seen before.

838
01:50:01,011 --> 01:50:02,345
That's right.

839
01:50:02,513 --> 01:50:06,683
Without surprises. Without animals or islands.

840
01:50:06,850 --> 01:50:09,519
Yes. The truth.

841
01:50:18,070 --> 01:50:20,863
So, what did you do?

842
01:50:25,035 --> 01:50:27,370
I told them another story.

843
01:50:28,205 --> 01:50:29,372
4 of us survived.

844
01:50:30,249 --> 01:50:32,792
The cook and the sailor were already aboard.

845
01:50:33,085 --> 01:50:34,919
The cook threw me a lifebuoy
and pulled me aboard. . .

846
01:50:35,087 --> 01:50:38,631
and Mother held on to some 
bananas and made it to the Lifeboat.

847
01:50:40,217 --> 01:50:43,219
The cook was a disgusting man.

848
01:50:43,387 --> 01:50:45,596
He ate a rat.

849
01:50:45,764 --> 01:50:48,891
We had food enough for weeks, but 
he found the rat in the first few days. . .

850
01:50:49,059 --> 01:50:52,729
and he killed it, dried it in the sun and ate it.

851
01:50:52,896 --> 01:50:55,106
He was such a brute, that man.

852
01:50:56,900 --> 01:50:59,235
But he was resourceful.

853
01:50:59,945 --> 01:51:03,573
It was his idea to build the raft to catch fish.

854
01:51:03,741 --> 01:51:06,951
We would have died in
those first few days without him.

855
01:51:09,246 --> 01:51:13,750
The sailor was the same man who 
brought rice and gravy, the Buddhist.

856
01:51:13,917 --> 01:51:17,295
We didn't understand much of what 
he said, only that he was suffering.

857
01:51:17,755 --> 01:51:19,922
He had broken his leg horribly in the fall.

858
01:51:20,090 --> 01:51:23,176
We tried to set it as best we could, but
the leg became infected. . .

859
01:51:23,594 --> 01:51:28,097
and the cook said that we 
had to do something or he'd die.

860
01:51:28,599 --> 01:51:29,640
The cook said he'd do it,

861
01:51:29,767 --> 01:51:32,101
but Mother and I had to hold the man down.

862
01:51:32,186 --> 01:51:34,771
And I believed him, we needed to do it.

863
01:51:35,439 --> 01:51:37,273
So. . .

864
01:51:38,942 --> 01:51:42,028
I kept saying, "I'm sorry, I'm sorry."

865
01:51:42,196 --> 01:51:46,032
And he just kept looking at me. 
His eyes were so. . .

866
01:51:49,203 --> 01:51:52,663
l'll never understand the point
of that man's suffering.

867
01:51:53,832 --> 01:51:56,042
I can still hear him.

868
01:51:56,794 --> 01:52:00,463
The happy Buddhist, he only ate rice and gravy.

869
01:52:05,677 --> 01:52:07,720
We didn't save him, of course.

870
01:52:07,888 --> 01:52:09,305
He died.

871
01:52:10,391 --> 01:52:12,475
The morning after, the cook 
caught his first dorado. . .

872
01:52:12,643 --> 01:52:15,686
and I didn't understand what  he 
had done at first, but Mother did. . .

873
01:52:15,854 --> 01:52:18,815
and I had never seen Mother so angry.

874
01:52:19,650 --> 01:52:21,567
"Stop whining and be happy," he said.

875
01:52:21,735 --> 01:52:24,570
"We need more food or we'll die.
That was the whole point."

876
01:52:24,738 --> 01:52:26,656
"What was the whole point?" Mother asked.

877
01:52:26,824 --> 01:52:30,910
"You let that poor boy die in 
order to get bait, you monster!"

878
01:52:32,413 --> 01:52:33,579
The cook got furious.

879
01:52:33,664 --> 01:52:35,665
He started towards her with his fist raised. . .

880
01:52:35,833 --> 01:52:38,876
and Mother slapped him hard, right across the face.

881
01:52:39,044 --> 01:52:40,920
I was stunned.

882
01:52:41,088 --> 01:52:43,548
I thought he was going to kill her right then.

883
01:52:44,883 --> 01:52:46,759
But he didn't.

884
01:52:48,679 --> 01:52:51,389
The cook didn't stop at bait either, no.

885
01:52:52,599 --> 01:52:54,183
The sailor. . .

886
01:52:55,936 --> 01:52:58,271
He went the same way the rat went.

887
01:53:01,024 --> 01:53:03,526
The cook was a resourceful man.

888
01:53:07,698 --> 01:53:09,866
It was a week later that he. . .

889
01:53:11,577 --> 01:53:13,744
Because of me.

890
01:53:13,912 --> 01:53:16,873
Because I couldn't hold on to a stupid turtle.

891
01:53:17,416 --> 01:53:19,917
It slipped out of my hands and swam away.

892
01:53:20,085 --> 01:53:22,420
And the cook came up and he punched 
me on the side of my head. . .

893
01:53:22,588 --> 01:53:24,797
and my teeth clacked and I saw stars.

894
01:53:24,965 --> 01:53:26,132
I thought he was going to hit me again. . .

895
01:53:26,300 --> 01:53:28,259
but Mother started pounding on him with her fists. . .

896
01:53:28,427 --> 01:53:30,219
screaming "Monster, monster!"

897
01:53:30,387 --> 01:53:31,846
She yelled at me to go to the raft.

898
01:53:33,765 --> 01:53:36,559
I thought she was coming with me,
or l'd never have. . .

899
01:53:39,480 --> 01:53:42,106
I don't know why I didn't make her go first.

900
01:53:44,109 --> 01:53:46,444
I think about that every day.

901
01:53:52,493 --> 01:53:56,162
I jumped over and turned back 
just as the knife came out.

902
01:54:00,083 --> 01:54:02,585
There wasn't anything I could do.

903
01:54:04,421 --> 01:54:06,422
I couldn't look away.

904
01:54:10,636 --> 01:54:13,095
He threw her body overboard.

905
01:54:14,765 --> 01:54:18,601
And then the sharks came. And I saw what they. . .

906
01:54:23,315 --> 01:54:24,941
I saw.

907
01:54:31,031 --> 01:54:33,616
The next day, I killed him.

908
01:54:34,785 --> 01:54:37,620
He didn't even fight back.
He knew he had gone too far. . .

909
01:54:37,788 --> 01:54:39,956
even by his own standards.

910
01:54:41,833 --> 01:54:43,376
He'd left the knife out on the bench,

911
01:54:43,460 --> 01:54:46,629
and I did to him what he did to the sailor.

912
01:54:49,383 --> 01:54:52,635
He was such an evil man, but worse still, he. . .

913
01:54:54,555 --> 01:54:57,348
He brought the evil out in me.

914
01:54:58,809 --> 01:55:01,185
And I have to live with that.

915
01:55:07,901 --> 01:55:10,653
I was alone in a Lifeboat. . .

916
01:55:11,530 --> 01:55:14,365
drifting across the Pacific Ocean.

917
01:55:15,075 --> 01:55:16,909
And I survived.

918
01:55:22,040 --> 01:55:25,334
After that, they had no more questions.

919
01:55:25,502 --> 01:55:29,171
The investigators didn't seem 
to like the story, exactly.

920
01:55:30,007 --> 01:55:34,510
But they thanked me,
they wished me well, and they left.

921
01:55:41,184 --> 01:55:43,352
So the stories. . .

922
01:55:46,023 --> 01:55:48,399
both the zebra and the sailor. . .

923
01:55:48,859 --> 01:55:50,776
broke their leg.

924
01:55:51,194 --> 01:55:54,405
And the hyena killed the zebra ,and the orangutan.

925
01:55:54,865 --> 01:55:58,868
So. . . the hyena is the cook.

926
01:55:59,202 --> 01:56:01,537
The sailor is the zebra.

927
01:56:01,872 --> 01:56:04,582
Your mother is the orangutan.

928
01:56:04,916 --> 01:56:08,044
And you are. . .

929
01:56:08,879 --> 01:56:11,297
the tiger.

930
01:56:15,302 --> 01:56:17,094
Can I ask you something?

931
01:56:18,597 --> 01:56:20,431
Of course.

932
01:56:20,599 --> 01:56:24,435
I've told you 2 stories about 
what happened out on the ocean.

933
01:56:24,603 --> 01:56:27,897
Neither explains what caused
the sinking of the ship. . .

934
01:56:28,065 --> 01:56:32,234
and no one can prove which 
story is true and which is not.

935
01:56:32,402 --> 01:56:35,738
In both stories, the ship sinks. . .

936
01:56:35,906 --> 01:56:38,824
my family dies and I suffer.

937
01:56:39,284 --> 01:56:40,743
True.

938
01:56:43,288 --> 01:56:45,581
So, which story do you prefer?

939
01:56:53,090 --> 01:56:55,257
The one with the tiger.

940
01:56:56,259 --> 01:56:58,511
That's the better story.

941
01:57:01,848 --> 01:57:03,599
Thank you.

942
01:57:04,184 --> 01:57:06,602
And so it goes with God.

943
01:57:18,323 --> 01:57:20,157
Mamaji was right.

944
01:57:21,159 --> 01:57:23,452
It's an amazing story.

945
01:57:24,871 --> 01:57:26,789
Will you really let me write it?

946
01:57:26,957 --> 01:57:28,374
Of course.

947
01:57:28,542 --> 01:57:31,794
Isn't that why Mamaji sent you here, after all?

948
01:57:35,799 --> 01:57:37,383
My wife is here.

949
01:57:37,551 --> 01:57:39,635
Do you want to stay for dinner?
She's an incredible cook.

950
01:57:39,803 --> 01:57:40,970
I didn't know you had a wife.

951
01:57:41,138 --> 01:57:43,347
And a cat and 2 children.

952
01:57:43,974 --> 01:57:46,350
So, your story does have a happy ending.

953
01:57:46,810 --> 01:57:49,478
Well, that's up to you.

954
01:57:49,813 --> 01:57:52,148
The story is yours now.

955
01:58:07,497 --> 01:58:08,539
Hmm.

956
01:58:09,541 --> 01:58:13,753
"Mr. Patel's is an astounding story
of courage and endurance. . .

957
01:58:13,920 --> 01:58:16,881
"unparalleled
in the history of shipwrecks.

958
01:58:17,048 --> 01:58:21,343
"Very few castaways can
claim to have survived so long at sea. . .

959
01:58:21,511 --> 01:58:24,054
"and none in the company. . .

960
01:58:24,222 --> 01:58:26,891
"of an adult Bengal tiger."

961
01:58:29,352 --> 01:58:30,644
Hi, Dad.

962
01:58:31,021 --> 01:58:33,731
We have a guest. Let me introduce you.

963
01:58:34,608 --> 01:58:35,733
Hi.
Hi.

964
01:58:36,026 --> 01:58:37,276
Nice to meet you.

965
01:58:37,444 --> 01:58:38,694
Adita.

966
01:58:39,696 --> 01:58:40,905
Ravi.

